In [14]:
# Extraction Patterns:

year = lambda x: datetime.strptime(x, "%Y-%m-%d" ).year

day_of_month = lambda x: datetime.strptime(x, "%Y-%m-%d").day

week_of_year = lambda x: pd.to_datetime(datetime.strptime(x, "%Y-%m-%d")).week

month = lambda x: datetime.strptime(x, "%Y-%m-%d").month
In [15]:

In [16]:
def birthday(date):
    # Get the current date
    now = datetime.utcnow()
    now = now.date()

    # Get the difference between the current date and the birthday
    age = dateutil.relativedelta.relativedelta(now, date)
    age = age.years

    return age

Verifying if simple [Sales] / [Quantity] can be done¶

WEIRD !!!!¶

The same item price [calculated as : SalesAmount / Quantity for a given Bill#], varies within the same year based on ??. !!¶

It's inconsitent !¶

E.g. above selected Product = PR-6785 has price as follows :-

###   YEAR  SALES   QUANTITY UNIT-PRICE GENDER  FAMILY-SIZE
###   2014  21.36   5        4.272      {CONSISTENT}
            17.088  4        4.272      

###   2015  6.408   4        1.602      Female  4 Family Size
            21.36   5        4.272      Male    4 Family Size
            6.408   4        1.602      Male    4 Family Size

### 2016    3.204   2        1.602      Male    4 Family Size
            8.544   2        4.272      FEMale  4 Family Size

### 2017    12.816  3        4.272    Irrespective of Males and Females 
            8.544   2        4.272      {CONSISTENT}

Gotcha!!,¶

> This is happening because the price of item (PR-6785), is low in middle months and increasing tremendously during month of December, but this is happening in 2015 only. !!¶

> In 2016, same item is costly in July, but cheap in September. So above stmnt is not generic.¶

> Same item in 2017 is having same UnitPrice again !!¶

> The same behaviour is not true for all items.¶

> And, its happening ony for OfficeSupplies but not crunched entire data at present(21stMar)¶

Very Important insights gained :-¶

1.) The item price depends on the month in which it is bought,¶

2.) The item price remains same throughout the month for that year.¶

3.) The item price "does NOT" depend on the age/gender/family-size of the customer, i.e. the item price has no relation with attributes of customer !!!¶

4. Item Unit Price has some relation with 'Billing_Month' of that year.¶

5. Creating 'Product_Unit_Price' in the dataset.¶

# Function that takes a list of dates and returns the most recent date.
def _getMostRecent_Date(listOfDates):    
    sorted_list = sorted(listOfDates)
    most_recent_date = sorted_list.pop()
    datetimeObject = pd.to_datetime(most_recent_date[0].astype(datetime))
    return datetimeObject.date().strftime('%m/%d/%Y')

# Function for Date Difference
def _diff_Dates(date1,date2):
    # Since the value stored in dataset is timestamp : 
    # type(customer_recency_DF.iloc[0,1]) is ::"pandas._libs.tslibs.timestamps.Timestamp"
    
    #Fetching Date from the Timestamp object
    dateFromTimestamp = date2.date()
    
    return (date1 - dateFromTimestamp).days

In [72]:
def _monetory_Score(customer_M_Value):
    if customer_M_Value <= 200:
        val = 1
    elif customer_M_Value > 200 and customer_M_Value <= 1147:
        val = 2
    elif customer_M_Value > 1147 and customer_M_Value <= 2257:
        val = 3
    elif customer_M_Value > 2257 and customer_M_Value <= 3786:
        val = 4
    else:
        val = 5
    return val
In [73]:
def _frequency_Score(customer_F_Value):
    if customer_F_Value <= 6:
        val = 1
    elif customer_F_Value > 6 and customer_F_Value <= 15:
        val = 2
    elif customer_F_Value > 16 and customer_F_Value <= 22:
        val = 3
    elif customer_F_Value > 22 and customer_F_Value <= 30:
        val = 4
    else:
        val = 5
    return val
In [74]:
def _recency_Score(customer_R_Value, quantile_Recency_Value):
    if customer_R_Value <= quantile_Recency_Value:
        val = 5
    elif customer_R_Value > quantile_Recency_Value and customer_R_Value <= 503:
        val = 4
    elif customer_R_Value > 503 and customer_R_Value <= 530:
        val = 3
    elif customer_R_Value > 530 and customer_R_Value <= 638:
        val = 2
    else:
        val = 1
    return val

for i, p in enumerate(['R_Score', 'F_Score', 'M_Score']):
    parameters = {'R_Score':'Recency', 'F_Score':'Frequency', 'M_Score':'Monetory'}
    y = customer_RFM_DF[p].value_counts().sort_index()
    x = y.index
    ax = axes[i]
    bars = ax.bar(x, y, color='silver')
    ax.set_frame_on(False)
    ax.tick_params(left=False, labelleft=False, bottom=False)
    ax.set_title('Distribution of {}'.format(parameters[p]),
                fontsize=14)
    for bar in bars:
        value = bar.get_height()
        if value == y.max():
            bar.set_color('firebrick')
        ax.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2,
                value - 5,
                '{}\n({}%)'.format(int(value), int(value * 100 / y.sum())),
               ha='center',

segt_map = {
    r'[1-2][1-2][1-2]': 'hibernating',
    r'[1-2][1-5][3-5]': 'at_risk',
    r'[1-2][4-5][4-5]': 'cannot_loose',
    r'3[1-2][1-2]': 'about_to_sleep',
    r'[2-3][2-3][2-3]': 'need_attention',
    r'[2-5][3-5][3-5]': 'loyal_customers',
    r'[3-4][1-2][1-2]': 'promising',
    r'[4-5]1[1-2]': 'new_customers',
    r'[3-5][2-4][2-4]': 'potential_loyalists',
    r'[3-5][1-2][3-5]': 'Recent_Good_Purchases_New',
    r'[3-5][3-4][3-5]': 'potential_Champions',
    r'[4-5][4-5][4-5]': 'champions',
    r'[1-2][3-5][1-2]': 'Shoppers_Relocated',
    r'[4-5][3-5][1-2]': 'Daily_Shoppers',
}

def _quantity_Score(customer_Q_Value):
    if customer_Q_Value <= 25:
        val = 1
    elif customer_Q_Value > 25 and customer_Q_Value <= 50:
        val = 2
    elif customer_Q_Value > 50 and customer_Q_Value <= 75:
        val = 3
    elif customer_Q_Value > 75 and customer_Q_Value <= 100:
        val = 4
    else:
        val = 5
    return val

Printing the Rules generated by the Decision Tree on Train Data¶

In [275]:
node_depth = np.zeros(shape=n_nodes, dtype=np.int64)
is_leaves = np.zeros(shape=n_nodes, dtype=bool)
stack = [(0, -1)]  # seed is the root node id and its parent depth
while len(stack) > 0:
    node_id, parent_depth = stack.pop()
    node_depth[node_id] = parent_depth + 1

    # If we have a test node
    if (children_left[node_id] != children_right[node_id]):
        stack.append((children_left[node_id], parent_depth + 1))
        stack.append((children_right[node_id], parent_depth + 1))
    else:
        is_leaves[node_id] = True

print("The binary tree structure has %s nodes and has "
      "the following tree structure:"
      % n_nodes)
print("\n")
for i in range(n_nodes):
    if is_leaves[i]:
        print("%snode=%s leaf node." % (node_depth[i] * "\t", i))
        print("\n")
    else:
        print("%snode=%s test node: go to node %s if X[:, %s] <= %s else to "
              "node %s."
              % (node_depth[i] * "\t",
                 i,
                 children_left[i],
                 feature[i],
                 threshold[i],
                 children_right[i],
                 ))
        print("\n")
print()

The binary tree structure has 25 nodes and has the following tree structure:


node=0 test node: go to node 1 if X[:, 0] <= 0.5 else to node 12.


	node=1 test node: go to node 2 if X[:, 6] <= 0.5 else to node 9.


		node=2 test node: go to node 3 if X[:, 5] <= 0.5 else to node 8.


			node=3 test node: go to node 4 if X[:, 10] <= 0.5 else to node 7.


				node=4 test node: go to node 5 if X[:, 3] <= 64.5 else to node 6.


					node=5 leaf node.


					node=6 leaf node.


				node=7 leaf node.


			node=8 leaf node.


		node=9 test node: go to node 10 if X[:, 2] <= 0.5 else to node 11.


			node=10 leaf node.


			node=11 leaf node.


	node=12 test node: go to node 13 if X[:, 2] <= 0.5 else to node 22.


		node=13 test node: go to node 14 if X[:, 5] <= 0.5 else to node 19.


			node=14 test node: go to node 15 if X[:, 12] <= 3244.21484375 else to node 18.


				node=15 test node: go to node 16 if X[:, 12] <= 1517.68408203125 else to node 17.


					node=16 leaf node.


					node=17 leaf node.


				node=18 leaf node.


			node=19 test node: go to node 20 if X[:, 4] <= 11.5 else to node 21.


				node=20 leaf node.


				node=21 leaf node.


		node=22 test node: go to node 23 if X[:, 7] <= 0.5 else to node 24.


			node=23 leaf node.


			node=24 leaf node.

¶

node=0 test node: go to node 1 if "RF_Segment_3" <= 0.5 else to node 18.                                                                                                                
    node=1 test node: go to node 2 if "RF_Segment_2" <= 0.5 else to node 18

            node=2 test node: go to node 3 if Demography_3 <= 0.5 else to node 10.                                                                                              
                    node=3 test node: go to node 4 if Total_Quantities_Purchased_Q <= 35.5 else to node 7.      

                            node=4 test node: go to node 5 if Demography_7 <= 0.5 else to node 6.           

                                    node=5 : "leaf node" : samples = 7.6%, class = y[6]

                                    node=6 : leaf node : samples = 8.0%, class = y[8]

                            node=7 test node: go to node 8 if Total_Quantities_Purchased_Q <= 49.5 else to node 9.
                                node=8 leaf node : samples = 13.7%, class = y[5]
                                node=9 leaf node : samples = 7.4%, class = y[10]

                    node=10 test node: go to node 11 if Total_Quantities_Purchased_Q <= 49.5 else to node 14.                               
                            node=11 test node: go to node 12 if Total_Quantities_Purchased_Q <= 32.5 else to node 13.                                                                               
                                    node=12 leaf node : samples = 7.0% , class = y[6]                                                                               
                                    node=13 leaf node : samples = 9.2%, class = y[1]                                                                        
                            node=14 leaf node : samples = 6.5%, class = y[2] : ]                                                                                
            node=15 test node: go to node 16 if Total_Quantities_Purchased_Q <= 28.5 else to node 17.                                                                                               
                    node=16 leaf node : samples = 7.3%, class = y[4]                                                                                        
                    node=17 leaf node : samples = 7.1% : class = y[4]

    node=18 test node: go to node 19 if Total_Quantities_Purchased_Q <= 79.5 else to node 22.                                                                                                               
            node=19 test node: go to node 20 if Gender_M <= 0.5 else to node 21.                                                                                                        
                    node=20 leaf node : class = y[0], samples = 8.5%                                                                                                
                    node=21 leaf node : class = y[9], samples = 7.3%

            node=22 leaf node : class = y[3], samples = 10.3%
